{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0e7d5608-fc66-4cad-95a0-3a82782e6a02","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** on `MauiAppBuilder` to map platform events to cross-platform hooks.\n\nIn your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android OnPause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android OnStop */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS DidEnterBackground */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Platform-specific blocks are guarded by `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives.\n- Each platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, `WillTerminate`, etc.) through the same fluent API.\n- This keeps all lifecycle wiring in one place without needing custom platform projects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ee21ce5-6879-4ea9-98e4-df5c1b3f5922","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task in the repo.","outputTokens":359},"id":"47c3a3d0-bbfb-401f-8960-dd89bc5d2dd4","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:39:56.487Z","parentId":"13706e90-2a75-4c9a-9a12-0f92d797c98d"}
